courses.name: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge

cmCourseInfo.description: Explore the thought processes, logic, motivation, techniques, analysis and impact of recent high-profile publications to gain insight into the enterprise of science. Outstanding scientists present recent high-impact papers, and students will examine the research in depth, focusing on the underlying questions, experimental approach, results and significance. Restricted to first-year students. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
cmCourseInfo.title: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry); permission of Department

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Term test will take place Tuesdays in person from 18:00 to 19:00 Toronto time (3 Tuesdays over the course).

Delivery Instructions

Lectures will be delivered online. Students will be expected to watch asynchronous lecture videos prior to class meetings; learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place in person Tuesdays from 18:00 to 19:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures 2h/week and optional synchronous help sessions 1h/week (these will be recorded). 

The final in-person assessment will be announced by the Faculty of Registrar’s office.

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Students will be expected to watch asynchronous lecture videos prior to in-person tutorials. Weekly in-person Physiology in Practice classes with professors will take place on Wednesdays from 14:00 to 15:00 at Con Hall. Term tests will be held in person/on campus and will take place Mondays, Wednesdays, or Fridays from 14:00 to 15:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures ~3h/week, Physiology in Practice classes 1h/week, and five (5) in-person one (1) hour tutorials per term.

The lecture videos will be posted to watch asynchronously. Physiology in Practice classes, tutorials, and tests will run in-person. The final in-person assessment will be announced by the Faculty of Registrar’s office.

Delivery Instructions

Approx 3 hours of online lecture recordings that can be viewed at any time.

1 hour Physiology in Practice session with the professor 2 to 3 pm at Con Hall in person

5 X 1 hour tutorials with TAs in-person throughout the term

In-person tests and exams. There are two in-person tests/term, one hour each generally set for Fridays, but might also be Mondays or Wednesdays — time 2 to 3 pm.

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I

cmCourseInfo.description: Focus on two topics: (1) The regulation of body weight/composition including the hormonal, neural and metabolic interactions between adipose tissue, the brain, the pancreas, and muscle. (2) Cardiovascular and respiratory control systems in adults and neonates in terms of feedback control systems, mechanisms, and clinical disorders.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II

cmCourseInfo.description: Focus on two topics: the brain and pregnancy. Delve into the physiology of the central nervous system along with associated diseases as model systems. Learn about fetal and maternal adaptations during pregnancy and the consequences of maladaptation. The course is designed for Physiology Specialist students, although permission is granted to other students upon Departmental approval.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1, MAT100-series

cmCourseInfo.description: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL420H1/LMP2100H
cmCourseInfo.title: Reproduction: Development and Function

courses.name: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion

primaryOrg.name: John H. Daniels Faculty of Architecture, Landscape, & Design

cmCourseInfo.description: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.
